node.text:
1) start with the slower/controlled crossover steps
2) Gradually speed it up and cover more distance laterally as you become comfortable
3) Turn it into a freestyle with cross over/cross under steps
4) REP IT

Typically I’d spend 3-5 min on a drill like this towards the end of a warmup. 

📝 Ankle mobility in sports is far more than linear dorsi flexion. We need to create shin angles over pinky toe side and over big toe side. 

I’ve seen a lot players who pass standard dorsi flexion range tests who actually have poor ankle mobility in sports. 

The drill I’m doing here is far more than just ankle mobility and creating good shin angles in games requires a combination of foot/ankle/hip mobility and stability that all ties together with proper timing/skill in the movement. 

The athletes who are the best at creating optimal shin angles didn’t build it through 3x5 drills in the weightroom (this isn’t bad... it’s just a very small part of the process). They build it through fluid/coordinated movement. 

For advanced ball handlers you could train this same thing through zig zag dribbling drills. But for average ball handlers, the ball control becomes the limiting factor which leads to slow/upright movement and the body angles don’t get challenged like they would without the ball.

Give this one a try. Let’s build 🔋.

🎥 @thatcalvinmai 
🎥 @suns @dbook

Here’s a SIMPLE drill you guys can do to build your lateral change of direction! In The Speed Code we have 2 key intro phases— 1) Healthy Human Foundations and 2) Freak Athlete Foundations. 

Healthy human phase is designed to get you moving optimally. Too many athletes are training specifically for their sport without developing optimal movement as a human first. This always leads to breakdowns in the body eventually. Building a base of movement quality, fitness and tissue tolerance can decrease our risk of injury long term. 

In phase 2, Our Freak Athlete Foundation phase aims to build the qualities needed for elite speed, agility and vertical jump. This is where we develop the physical/neuromuscular traits needed for high level athleticism and expose the body to more specific stresses in order to prepare the body for the rest of the program. 

I’m excited to get you guys going on the program. We’re almost ready for launch! @spellmanperformance and I are excited to create some monsters in ALL sports. Let’s build.

This advice is actually 🔑 for players of all sizes, but especially undersized players. You can’t be small AND lack quickness. End to end speed doesn’t need to be great but the quickness has to be there to hang defensively at the highest levels. Yes, there’s many more things you need beyond quickness... but think of a requisite level of quickness as your key to get on the floor in the first place. 

Good news is we CAN significantly improve quickness. And it happens through a combination of body (actual physiological changes) and brain (perceptual abilities). If you’re improving your brain quickness (perception-action) we’re “slowing the game down”, which improves anticipation and reaction abilities. This comes from specific reaction training, film work, game experience, etc.

If you’re improving your body quickness you’re changing actual physiological traits (neuromuscular gains, musculotendon, etc) This always shows up in drills and testing situations but doesn’t automatically transfer to live play. 

We want to attack both brain and body quickness! But body quickness has diminishing returns, while brain quickness continues to improve across your entire career. I’ve had numerous NBA PG clients that I can still outperform on all quickness tests, but they’re quicker than me in games. Why? They anticipate better. They see more frames per second than me. They’ve guarded more high level moves than me, which makes their reaction speed far better. 

In our upcoming program the speed code we attack both brain and body quickness. Can’t wait to get you guys on the program!

For the full 15 minute video check out TheEdgeU.com! Continuing our conversation w/ squats and approach jumps, in this video we discussed the importance of joint angle specificity. 

Deep squats “work” your muscles better. But they massively under train the joint angles that actually matter for the approach jump. The literature tells us that in beginners training in a deep range of motion and long muscle length leads to gains at multiple other joint angles and shorter muscle lengths... but in trained individuals we only see strength improvements at or near the joint angle being trained. So getting super strong in deep ranges won’t translate much to strength in partial ranges, especially considering that we only train these partial ranges at 70% max load when deep squatting. Now, deep squats and parallel do have advantages such as improved hypertrophy (which could be good or could be bad for approach jump). Also, deeper squats may be better for injury reduction. In this series we’re strictly looking at approach jumps to determine what exercises can actually increase “force potential”. In the next part of the series I’ll talk about why I don’t use quarter squats year round and give you some safer alternatives that may work even better than bilateral quarter squats! Stay tuned.

🐰 @maxwellpearce @hamilt0njr

Let’s discuss...

(For the full 15 minute video checkout TheEdgeU.com- link in bio). In the past we’ve discussed squats and jumping quite a bit on EdgeU and @strong_by_science and I have discussed it from a muscle standpoint, biomechanical stand point, individual joint torque standpoint and now from a force output point of view. Remember this particular discussion is ONLY looking at it from a force perspective... it gets more complicated than this!

From my research pulling from hundreds of elite athlete force plate tests and DSI testing, I believe heavy squats to parallel actually don’t increase “force potential” for APPROACH jumps in well-trained athletes. The peak forces are just far too low and far too slow. Now, most coaches know heavy squats won’t directly translate but some believe it increase "force potential". But the problem is that peak forces on heavy squats to parallel are normally even LOWER than the peak force of a standing jump. And approach jump peak forces are way beyond anything we could see in a parallel squat. So the idea that heavy parallel squats increases force potential must be hinged on the idea that we produce force over a longer period of time. I’d agree that a standing vertical jump may increase because a lot of heavy deep squats can train the athlete to get lower and produce force over a longer period of time (increase impulse by widening the curve). But in approach jumping we have strict time constraints on ground contact, which means we usually can’t increase impulse by widening the curve... we can only increase impulse by producing a higher peak force. So exercises that don’t involve high peak forces likely don’t have much transfer to approach jumping. 

This doesn’t mean half/deep squats are bad! There’s plenty of reasons to use them. But don’t expect your approach jumps to significantly increase by moving heavier weight in full range squats. Quarter squats would translate much better because of the high peak forces, but it’s STILL just potential. We typically see benefits when an athlete comes in weak and climbs to a 1.75x bodyweight quarter squat. Beyond 2x BW 1/4 squat safety might become an issue + low return on investment.

node.title: Do heavy squats really increase “force potential” in jumping?

node.text:
Coach yells “PRACTICE AT GAME SPEED”. 

Players start performing everything at 100% speed.

Game time comes and they take 10 shots, ALL at different speeds. Some shots they had space to slowly step into it. Other shots they had to rush to get off. 

Game speed isn’t one speed. It’s a wide range of speeds. 

👉I call this training method “Speed Range”. Using a metronome we get the athlete to perform a skill at the highest possible pace AND the slowest possible pace. I’m demonstrating a ball handling drill, but this method can be used for nearly any skill. 

A vocalist works on their range by hitting the highest possible note and the lowest possible note. That doesn’t guarantee they will use those high and low notes in their next song. But when you expand the range you now have options. Same goes with basketball skills. 

This method “stabilizes a skill” at the fastest possible pace and at the slowest pace to increase our maximum range. Then eventually we implement more randomized practice and go back and forth between different paces.

Every athlete has their preferred speed. Some are good dribblers or good shooters at slow speeds. Got time to take the shot? It’s going in. Gotta get it up quick? Now it’s a low percentage shot.

Some are on the other end of the spectrum. They’re skilled at high speeds but can’t operate at low speeds. Gotta sprint into a catch and shoot? Easy money. Wide open with all the time in the world 😥? Brick. 

The slow nervous system guy’s scouting report usually says “speed him up”. They might be the most skilled player when they can operate at their preferred cadence… but speed them up and their skills fall off. 

The fast nervous system guy can’t get himself to slow down. Slow gives you options. Slow gives you more time to make reads. KD off a slow lateral float has TIME to read primary and help side defenders. 

There’s some rare players that blend speeds extremely well. These are the Harden’s, Steph’s, Dame’s, etc. 

It’s not just change of pace. A lot of people can change pace. It’s how stabilized your skills are at fast speeds AND slow speeds.

Drop a 🦑 if you want more insight into how I use this Speed Range Theory. Go build.

Drop a 🦑 if you watched it more than once! 

If I had to choose 1 drill for a better functioning brain (in sports and life) while also improving athleticism and reducing risk of injury it would probably be this drill. Sounds CRAZY right? Hear me out…

Copy Cat Locomotion👈
-Partner creates a pattern (my wife was my partner). The pattern has to be rhythmic. Can include skips, bounds, crawling…. Whatever you want (has to be a unique pattern every time). The other partner has to learn the pattern in under 1 minute, then you guys both rep it out for 40 yards x 3-5 reps.

Then you become the pattern creator and they have to copy you. Repeat for 10-20 minutes. 

The impact this has on the brain is unreal. Pattern creation and pattern recognition, paired with high movement variability is a brain and body CHEAT CODE. 

I’ve heard neuroscientists talk about how learning a new language is like a software update for that part of the brain. You don’t just learn THAT language, you all of a sudden start remembering English words you learned 15 years ago. You fixed “the bugs” with your software update. 

This drill will expose you to a bunch of rhythmic patterns that your brain hasn’t  even thought about doing. And when you master a new movement pattern, it doesn’t just get you moving more fluid in THAT pattern, it can potentially fix “bugs” in other previously learned patterns as well. It’s a software update for your movement skills. 

At the top of the athleticism/injury reduction food chain is FLUIDITY and body control. Repetition is important, but doing the same couple patterns over and over again doesn’t allow you to unlock NEW levels of movement fluidity. Your brain/body also stops LEARNING HOW TO LEARN if you don’t force it to learn new movements frequently! 

You might be thinking “but I can’t bound in all directions like you did in the video”. Well, you don’t have to. In fact, my wife created this specific pattern. For her it was more of a baby bound… just small steps, no jumping or long bounding. Once I mastered the pattern, I then scaled it up and started doing longer bounds. But this drill is scalable to all athletes and non athletes!

Get those hips moving better! It’s amazing how much more effortless and athletic all movements become when we develop adequate rotational hip mobility.

This warmup/prep drill is great for getting the hips (and spine) to rotate more effectively. Most athletes do hip rotation mobility work, but it’s usually focused on femur moving on the pelvis (drills like 90/90 rotations).
What’s often neglected and arguably even more important, is drills like this that emphasize a fixed femur with the pelvis (acetabulum) rotating on that fixed femur. 

Every step we take, every cut we make and every jump requires some degree of pelvis on femur rotation. 

I’ve been using different variations of these drills as warmups for a few years and have seen some great results! I know @vernongriffith4 has some good variations of these as well, so that’s a good resource to check out. 

@spenfree12 been making some big progress in movement quality and athleticism this year! The grind continues.

This is how young kids should be training off the court! We’ve known for decades the negative effects of early sport specialization when it comes to longevity. From the outside looking in, it’s easy to say “kids should sign up for soccer, gymnastics, etc.” But in reality, it’s difficult to do with the current model of year round AAU. And let’s be very real, playing year round basketball is a HUGE advantage in terms of skill level and basketball IQ. These kids are so much more skilled than ever before. The high amount of basketball played before high school allows these kids to process the game at a faster rate than those who didn’t play as much basketball as kids. There’s no reaction or agility training that will ever compare to high quality hours played at a young age. 

So if we take them out of basketball for 6 months to play other sports, it’s very likely that they could fall behind and miss out on some crucial windows for development. Remember, if you’re trying to master ANY skill… doing it only half the year probably doesn’t make the most sense. 

This is why I like to microdose different sports into the day to day off-court training for young athletes. Add in gymnastic type movements, soccer, receiver/corner drills, etc. 

Expose kids to the movements they’re missing out on by not being able to play multiple organized sports. Your movement bank will grow, which will help you long term on the court and decrease risk of injury throughout your entire career. 

Generally speaking, I’d advise to expose kids to as many sports as possible from ages 3-10. If they clearly show a love for basketball and decide that’s what they want to do, I’d go the year round AAU route. But if they go that route, the club has to manage workload effectively and the player should still be exposed to different sports as their “training” and free play off the court.

node.text:
Day 24 of #30Days30Drills we got @amari__bailey finishing a workout with some towel curls. 

We use a towel grip on certain exercises to challenge finger/hand/forearm strength (we typically start on towel curls, progressing to rows, then progressing to pull up iso holds). 

Hand/finger strength is important for hoopers, not just for performance enhancement but also for injury risk reduction. Keep in mind, our lower body is exposed to millions of pounds  of force through the sport itself (jumping, running, cutting, etc). Wolfs Law (bone) and Davis’s Law (Soft Tissue) tells us that bone and soft tissue will remodel according to the manner in which they are mechanically stressed. So yes, lower body strength training is great… but our lower body will already be getting some requisite loading through the sport itself that will remodel tissue and build some level of strength and resiliency. However, the upper body gets very little loading through the sport. Wrist, hand, fingers get close to no loading in basketball, which means it has to come from the weightroom. 

Wrist and finger injuries are extremely common in basketball. To reduce the risk, we have to load it to build durability! That being said, don’t use this as an excuse to go become a bodybuilder. As always, everything in moderation. Go build.

Mobility drills that cause longer lasting gains = 🔑. Strength training isn’t just about force output, we can also use it to improve movement quality and mobility.

Day 23 of #30Days30Drills we got @kpangos on a front foot elevated split squat with hip shift. Elevating the front foot and turning towards the lead leg will challenge hip internal rotation and hip flexion. 

Hip IR is usually very limited in most people and all the 90/90 IR drills can be nice but usually provides very little lasting gains. Adding in exercises like this one has lead to longer lasting mobility improvements in a lot of our athletes.

Not sure who originally came up with the FFE hip shift to bias IR, but I’ve picked up some great cues from @conor_harris_ . I have a program featuring Conor releasing soon that will make a difference in how you move! Stay tuned.

node.text:
Tag someone you’ll blow by with your first step 👀. Day 22 of #30Days30Drills we got @xrm22 on the resisted first steps with the @flexlinefitness (in Fat Don’t Fly and Speed Code we do similar variations with bands). 

We do a good amount of sled work, but there’s a few things we get with this drill that we can’t get with a sled:

1) Better rotation from the hip and torso. By starting with only 1 hand on the bench (opposite arm), we free up the torso to rotate over the stance leg on the load up. This position gives us the hip rotation (pelvis rotating on a fixed femur) that we we would see on a first step blow by. Coaches often repeat the term “load to explode”, but “load” isn’t just flexion and “explode” isn’t just extension. The rotational components are just as important! 

2) Eccentric loading. Sleds are a great tool, but it’s primarily concentric (which could be good if you want to decrease soreness). But with the cable we have to control on the way back, which gets us some nice eccentric loading. Particularly, I like that we get some isometric/eccentric loading through the lower leg while the foot is behind the hip. Being strong and stable in this position is important for Achilles injury reduction in my opinion.

Day 21 of #30Days30Drills we got @tackofall99 working on defensive movement skills. 

There’s 3 main things we’re working on with this drill—

1) Hip flip push out into the lateral slide. Both feet briefly lift off the ground to allow a quicker hip flip, outside foot lands and pushes you into the lateral slide. The quickness of this initial hip flip can often be the difference between a blow by or a stop. See my full presentation on @theedgeu talking about a concept I call “positional delay”. This falls under that category.

2) Transition from a slide into a cross step to run with the ball handlers while staying glued with the upper body (aka lower body turns to run, torso stays glued to offensive player). Bigs have to contain quick guards coming downhill at them on ball screens and you won’t always be able to slide with them, cross step turn and run has to be a focal point of agility training for bigs especially. 

3) Every now and then we use a dowel for accountability to improve footwork/speed while hands are above the head. Even the quickest players struggle to move laterally with the hands above the head. Everything gets slower and change of direction becomes far more difficult. It’s not that we want to always have hands high, but from time to time you’ll have to contest while your lower body is still moving. This drill exaggerates this skill and makes it far easier come game time. I wouldn’t overdo it with the dowel, but it’s nice to throw in for a few sets here and there. 

Tacko continues to add layers to his movement skills every year. His rate of progression has been impressive!

Day 20 of #30Days30Drills we got @amari__bailey doing some extensive hops on the vertimax (can also be performed with light dumbbells or without weight).

Extensive plyo’s (low intensity, longer duration) is great for building healthy/springy muscles and tendons. In basketball our tendons are exposed to insanely high spring forces. Proper progressions in extensive plyo’s gives us the graded exposure we need to handle these forces.

There’s a reason jump rope has been used for centuries by all types of athletes— it works. Jump rope is one of the fundamental methods of extensive plyo’s. However, we can take these concepts and make them even more specific to basketball by doing single leg extensives, multi-directional extensives, knee dominant or ankle dominant, etc.

One important point on this particular drill— back foot should be elevated for a second point of support. I’m not a fan of single leg repeat jumps that involve a knee bend without the second point of support (I’m ok with ankle dominant repeats, but not knee dominant). Usually if I use single leg plyo’s it’s cyclical and moving forward. This gives us the rotation over the stance leg and the counterbalance needed to make the lower body mechanics look good. On stationary knee dominant repeat jumps, we are forced into a large Q-angle that I think adds unnecessary and unrealistic stresses on the knee. But this is all solved by simply putting your back foot on a box. Or in the case of ankle/Achilles dominant extensives, we would throw the front foot on a box. 

Good talk. Go build.

Can you hit all 3 spots and finish with a 1 dribble dunk? @everybody_hatechriss has a super effective penultimate step (second to last step) that allows him to build momentum from short approach distances but also allows him to cover more distance in less dribbles when needed. A longer penultimate step isn’t always needed for maximal jump height, but for many in-game situations having the ability to push through the penultimate to cover more distance in less steps can be a game changer.
